'''John Barnes Linnett''' ({{circa|1831}} – ) was a British [[lithograph]] [[printer (publisher)|printer]] based in [[Birmingham]], [[England]]. Although the French [[Pierre-Hubert Desvignes]] is generally credited with being the inventor of the [[flip book]], Linnett was the first to [[patent]] the invention, in 1868, under the name of ''kineograph''.<ref>{{cite book |last1=McDonough |first1=John |last2=Egolf |first2=Karen |title=The Advertising Age Encyclopedia of Advertising |date=2015 |publisher=Routledge |isbn=9781135949068 |page=81 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=HZLtCQAAQBAJ&pg=PA81&dq=John+Barnes+Linnett |accessdate=2 July 2018 |language=en}}</ref><ref>{{cite book |title=Chronological Index of Patents Applied for and Patents Granted |date=1869 |publisher=G.E. Eyre and W. Spottiswoode |page=65 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=FsXj0P4OwKQC&pg=PA65&dq=John+Barnes+Linnett |accessdate=2 July 2018 |language=en}}</ref>

He was born in [[Austrey]], Warwickshire.<ref>''1851 England Census''</ref>

Linnett died of [[pneumonia]]. His wife sold the patent to an American.

